      "response": "Perfect! I've identified the root cause. Here's my diagnosis:\n\n## ROOT CAUSE\n\n**File:** `src/ucl_parser.c:1636-1643` (function `ucl_parse_after_value`)\n\nThe parser's `ucl_parse_after_value` function requires an explicit delimiter (`;`, `,`, newline, comment, or `}`, `]`) before the next configuration element. However, when a macro like `.include` appears directly after a closing brace `}` without a delimiter, the parser encounters the `.` character and throws \"delimiter is missing\" error because `.` is not recognized as a valid continuation\u2014it's checked in the \"Anything else\" branch which demands a prior separator.\n\nThe test case `14.in` has:\n```\nsection {\n# key = value;\n}.include(try=true) \"./1.in\"\n```\n\nThe `.` starting `.include` appears immediately after `}` with no delimiter in between, triggering the error at line 1639.\n\n## LOCAL FIX\n\nIn `src/ucl_parser.c`, modify the `ucl_parse_after_value` function to recognize `.` as a valid macro start without requiring a prior separator. Add this check before the \"Anything else\" branch (before line 1636):\n\n```c\nelse if (*p == '.') {\n    /* Start of a macro - macros don't require delimiters */\n    return true;\n}\n```\n\nThis allows the state machine to exit `ucl_parse_after_value` and transition back to the KEY state, where `ucl_parse_key` (line 1014-1019) will properly recognize and parse the macro.\n\n## GLOBAL FIX\n\nRestructure the `ucl_parse_after_value` function to treat `.` as an implicit statement separator. Macros are syntactically equivalent to new key-value pairs and should not require explicit delimiters between them and preceding values. The fix prevents the class of parse errors where macros (`.include`, `.try_include`, etc.) cannot directly follow closing braces without punctuation.",
